         <abstract>
            <p>It is well known among academics that the use of the net present value (NPV) criterion employing the weighted average cost of capital is consistent with shareholder wealth maximization for accept-reject decisions. In general, however, this procedure may not yield correct choices among mutually exclusive alternatives or under conditions of capital rationing. Previous work has shown that the discrepancy between NPV and the gain to shareholders arises from the interaction of financing and investment decisions. We restate these arguments in an intuitively appealing way and derive the pattern of sinking fund payments that guarantees that NPV equals the change in shareholder wealth, thus making it a valid criterion for choosing among mutually exclusive options.</p>
         </abstract>
